snippet.textDisplay:
Your good editing doesn‘t compensate at all the factually wrong content in many points.

>>> 8:42 „players that immediately after tested positive“

WRONG: if the basketball player tested *immediately* positive for COVID he would not be allowed to fly from Belgrade to Athens (where he stayed in isolation). Therefore, the player likely tested positive after flying to Athens. Barcelona Club only reported on Dec 16 about the infection.

>>> 8:45 „Knowing this, Djokovic took a rapid antigen test on the 16th but before getting his results back he attended…“

WRONG: Djokovic took a PCR test on Dec 16 but didn‘t get the results until 17th in the evening. Until then, he took a rapid antigen test on the 16th and 17th before attending the events, both were negative!
Yes, going to the 40min L‘Equipe interview on the 18th in his own Tennis Club was indeed a breach if Serbian Covid protocols.

>>> 9:22 the initial entry visa with the 14 day travel question was filled in in November (2 months before arrival). It was filled in by his managemant secretary who didn‘t update that answer before arrival. When an European applies for an US-ESTA visum it is also often done weeks in advance. Things in life can change. There was no deliberate false answer. The form Djokovic filled in before departure was correct and also declared the travel within the last 14 days.

>>> 10:42 WRONG: Judge A. Kelly was not involved with the 2nd appeal. He passed it over to the Federal Court. The denied him „natural justice“ (if you don‘t know what it means you didn‘t understand the whole 2nd part of the story).

Friendly hint: ready the court documents before blabbering the same nonsense all other tennis reporters and tabloid media do.

FAIL!

snippet.textDisplay:
I feel it was a pretty important detail that Djokovic gained the exemption by claiming to have tested positive for Covid-19. But the test certificates he provided were deemed by the BBC likely to be fabrications.

The test result meant that he was electronically cleared to enter Australia. But border force then detained him and the rest was well explained.

But crucially, he claimed to have contracted Covid. Then of course never mentioned it or withdrew from media appearances etc. pretty sketchy.

He also continued to travel, which contradicted the box he ticked on his visa application.

Here is link to the bbc article which compared Djokovic’s tests to others carried out in Serbia and found that the serial numbers on the tennis player’s tests did not fit chronologically with the order of other tests carried out in Serbia.

https://www.bbc.com/news/59999541

Basically the tests are not from the date printed on the certificate.

The Serbian authorities say the tests are not fabrications and also, that they are not backdated. But have not offered an explanation for the out of order serial numbers. 

So while the Australian government did issue a visa. The visa was probably issued on the basis of forged documents. Not to mention the lie on the visa application about travel.

This is a very major detail. In effect, the Serbian government has lied to the Australian authorities if these documents are fake. That is a significant thing for one country to do to another.

So as an Australian. I did not feel sorry for Djokovic. Many people here have not seen family in a long time. I myself couldn’t actually leave Australia to visit family.

I wish no exemption existed. But as it did, I a knowledge that Djokovic was entitled to apply for it. And that once he landed here, the way he was treated was framed by one of our high court judges to be less than fair.

However, ultimately our High Court found that the federal government was entitled to deport him. I wish it had never gotten so muddled and confused but, I was pleased.

Then finding out he only got here by lying, well, I regret ever feeling sympathy for him and thinking he had been scape goated. He was in on a conspiracy to lie about Covid tests, backed by his government for his own benefit. That’s not a victim of his own fake. That’s a man who nearly got away with exploiting his power and profile.
